Certainly! Below is a simple HTML and JavaScript code snippet that creates a single pixel that scans across the screen horizontally, line by line. The pixel changes color as it moves, and eventually forms the message "HELLO" on the screen.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Pixel Message</title>
  <style>
    #canvas {
      border: 1px solid black;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

<canvas id="canvas" width="300" height="200"></canvas>

<script>
  const canvas = document.getElementById('canvas');
  const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
  let x = 0;
  let y = 0;
  const message = "HELLO";
  let messageIndex = 0;

  function drawPixel() {
    // Change color for each pixel
    ctx.fillStyle = `rgb(${Math.floor(Math.random() * 256)}, ${Math.floor(Math.random() * 256)}, ${Math.floor(Math.random() * 256)})`;

    // Draw the pixel
    ctx.fillRect(x, y, 1, 1);

    // Check if it's time to draw a letter from the message
    if (x % 60 === 0 && y % 40 === 0 && messageIndex < message.length) {
      ctx.font = "30px Arial";
      ctx.fillStyle = "black";
      ctx.fillText(message[messageIndex], x, y + 30);
      messageIndex++;
    }

    // Move to the next pixel
    x++;
    if (x >= canvas.width) {
      x = 0;
      y++;
    }

    // Stop if we've reached the end of the canvas
    if (y < canvas.height) {
      requestAnimationFrame(drawPixel);
    }
  }

  drawPixel();
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### How to Run the Code:

1. Copy the above code into a text editor.
2. Save the file with an `.html` extension, for example, `pixel_message.html`.
3. Open the saved HTML file in a web browser.

The pixel will start at the top-left corner and move across the screen, changing colors as it goes. It will form the message "HELLO" as it moves.

