Creating a "Magic Eye" (also known as a stereogram) image is a bit more complex than the previous example. Stereograms work by repeating patterns at varying intervals to create the illusion of depth when viewed correctly. However, I can provide you with a simplified example that attempts to mimic the effect.

Here's a basic HTML and JavaScript code snippet:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Magic Eye</title>
  <style>
    #canvas {
      border: 1px solid black;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

<canvas id="canvas" width="800" height="600"></canvas>

<script>
  const canvas = document.getElementById('canvas');
  const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
  let x = 0;
  let y = 0;

  function drawPixel() {
    // Generate a random color for each pixel
    const color = `rgb(${Math.floor(Math.random() * 256)}, ${Math.floor(Math.random() * 256)}, ${Math.floor(Math.random() * 256)})`;
    ctx.fillStyle = color;

    // Draw the pixel
    ctx.fillRect(x, y, 1, 1);

    // Create a repeating pattern to mimic Magic Eye effect
    if (x > 0 && x < canvas.width && y > 0 && y < canvas.height) {
      ctx.fillStyle = ctx.getImageData(x - 10, y, 1, 1).data;
      ctx.fillRect(x + 10, y, 1, 1);
    }

    // Move to the next pixel
    x++;
    if (x >= canvas.width) {
      x = 0;
      y++;
    }

    // Stop if we've reached the end of the canvas
    if (y < canvas.height) {
      requestAnimationFrame(drawPixel);
    }
  }

  drawPixel();
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### How to Run the Code:

1. Copy the above code into a text editor.
2. Save the file with an `.html` extension, for example, `magic_eye.html`.
3. Open the saved HTML file in a web browser.

This is a very simplified example and doesn't create a true "Magic Eye" effect, but it does attempt to mimic the repeating patterns that are characteristic of stereograms.

